window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2025>SECTION A>1>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2025","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : BINARY OPERATIONS","question":"A binary operation * is defined on the set of real numbers, R, by x * y = 2x + 2y - xy/5.  Find the:    inverse of x under the operation *;    (Please leave your answer in this form: (a^b + c)/(d + e)^f)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"x*y=2x+2y-xy5  To find the inverse of x under the operation *, we first need to determine the identity element.    x * e = x    x*e=2x+2e-xe5  2x+2e-xe5=x  2e-xe5=x-2x  (2-x5)e=-x  e=-x2 - x/5  e=-x(10 - x)/5  e=-5x10 - x  Let x\u22121 be the inverse of x. Then x \u2217 x\u22121 = e    x\u2217x\u22121=2x+2x\u22121-xx\u221215  2x+2x\u22121-xx\u221215=e  2x+2x\u22121-xx\u221215=-5x10 - x  2x\u22121-xx\u221215=-5x10 - x-2x  (2-x5)x\u22121=-5x - 2x(10 - x)10 - x  (10 - x5)x\u22121=-5x - 20x + 2x210 - x  (10 - x5)x\u22121=2x2 - 25x10 - x  x\u22121=2x2 - 25x10-x\u00f710 - x5  x\u22121=2x2 - 25x10 - x\u00d7510 - x  \u2234x\u22121=10x2 - 125x(10  - x)2","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2025>SECTION A>1>b","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2025","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : BINARY OPERATIONS","question":"A binary operation * is defined on the set of real numbers, R, by x * y = 2x + 2y - xy/5.  Find the:  truth set when m * 7 = -2 * m.    (**Please leave your answer in this form: {a})","images":[],"marking_scheme":"m*7=-2*m  Sincex*y=2x+2y-xy5  \u21d22m+2(7)-m(7)5=2(-2)+2m-(-2)m5  \u21d22m+14-7m5=-4+2m+2m5  Collectliketerms  \u21d22m-7m5-2m-2m5=-4-14  \u21d2-9m5=-18  \u21d2-9m=-90  \u21d2m=-90-9=10  The truth set contains only one value.    The truth set is {10}.","marks":"3","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2025>SECTION A>2","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2025","type":"Theory","sub_label":"2","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : PERMUTATION AND COMBINATIONS.","question":"Given that xC2 + xC3 - 4x = 0, where x is a positive integer, find the value of x.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"xC2 + xC3 - 4x = 0    \u21d2x!(x - 2)!2!+x!(x - 3)!3!-4x=0  \u21d2x(x - 1)(x - 2)!(x - 2)!2!+x(x - 1)(x - 2)(x - 3)!(x - 3)!3!  \u21d2x(x - 1)2!+x(x - 1)(x - 2)3!-4x=0  \u21d2x(x - 1)2+x(x - 1)(x - 2)6-4x=0  Divide by x:    \u21d2x - 12+(x - 1)(x - 2)6-4=0  \u21d2x - 12+x2 - 2x - x + 26-4=0  \u21d2x - 12+x2 - 3x + 26-4=0  Multiply by 6:    \u21d2 3(x - 1) + x2 - 3x + 2 - 24 = 0    \u21d2 3x - 3 + x2 - 3x + 2 - 24 = 0    \u21d2 x2 - 25 = 0    \u21d2 x2 = 25    \u21d2 x = &radic;25&nbsp;    \u21d2 x = \u00b15    Therefore, the positive integer value for x is 5.","marks":"6","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2025>SECTION A>3>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2025","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : FUNCTIONS","question":"Afunctionfisdefinedby f(x) =72px + r,where  p and r are constants. Given that  f (6) = 12 and  f (7) = 9, find:    the values of p and r.    (Please leave your answer in this form: p = a, r = b)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"f(x) =72px + r   f(6) =72p(6) + r=12  \u21d2726p + r=12  \u21d2 12(6p + r) = 72    \u21d2 6p + r = 6 ----- (i)     f(7) =72p(7) + r=9  \u21d2727p+r=9  \u21d2 9(7p + r) = 72    \u21d2 7p + r = 8 ----- (ii)    Substract (i) from (ii)    \u21d2 p = 2    Substitute (2) for p in equation (i)    \u21d2 6(2) + r = 6    \u21d2 12 + r = 6    \u21d2 r = 6 - 12    \u21d2 r = -6    Therefore, the values of p and r are 2 and -6 respectively.","marks":"3","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2025>SECTION A>3>b","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2025","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : FUNCTIONS","question":"Afunctionfisdefinedby f(x) =72px + r,where  p and r are constants. Given that  f (6) = 12 and  f (7) = 9, find:   f -1(53)    (Please leave your answer to 1 d.p)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"f(x) =72px + r  \u21d2 f(x) =722x - 6  Let y = f(x)    \u21d2y=722x - 6  \u21d2 y(2x - 6) = 72    \u21d2 2xy - 6y = 72    \u21d2 2xy = 72 + 6y    x=72 + 6y2y  \u21d2 f(x) -1=72 + 6x2x  \u21d2 f(53) -1=72 + 6(5/3)2(5/3)  \u21d2 f(53) -1=72 + 1010/3  \u21d2 f(53) -1=8210/3  \u21d2 f(53) -1=82 \u00d7 310  \u21d2 f(53) -1=24610  \u2234 f(53) -1=123524.6","marks":"3","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2025>SECTION A>4","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2025","type":"Theory","sub_label":"4","group":"","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : RATIONAL FUNCTIONS","question":"Resolve2x - 725x - 24 - 6x2intopartialfractions.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"2x \u2212 725x \u2212 24 \u2212 6x2  \u21d22x \u2212 7\u22126x2 + 25x \u2212 24=2x \u2212 7\u2212(6x2 \u2212 25x + 24)  \u21d22x \u2212 7\u2212(2x \u2212 3)(3x \u2212 8)=\u2212(2x \u2212 7)(2x \u2212 3)(3x \u2212 8)  \u21d2\u2212(2x \u2212 7)(2x \u2212 3)(3x \u2212 8)=A(2x \u2212 3)+B(3x \u2212 8)  \u21d2\u2212(2x \u2212 7)(2x \u2212 3)(3x \u2212 8)=A(3x \u2212 8) + B(2x \u2212 3)(2x \u2212 3)(3x \u2212 8)  \u21d2 \u2212(2x \u2212 7) = A(3x \u2212 8) + B(2x \u2212 3) ----- (i)    TofindA,set2x\u22123=0\u21d22x=3\u21d2x=32  Substitutex=32inequation(i)  \u21d2\u2212(2(32)\u22127)=A(3(32)\u22128)+B(2(32)\u22123)  \u21d2\u2212(3\u22127)=A(92\u22128)+B(3\u22123)  \u21d2\u2212(\u22124)=A(\u221272)+B(0)  \u21d24=\u22127A2  \u21d28=\u22127A  \u21d2A=\u221287  TofindB,set3x\u22128=0\u21d23x=8\u21d2x=83  Substitutex=83inequation(i)  \u21d2\u2212(2(83)\u22127)=A(3(83)\u22128)+B(2(83)\u22123)  \u21d2\u2212(163\u22127)=A(8\u22128)+B(163\u22123)  \u21d2\u2212(\u221253)=A(0)+B(73)  \u21d253=7B3  \u21d25=7B  \u21d2B=57  So, the partial fraction decomposition is:    \u21d22x \u2212 725x \u2212 24 \u2212 6x2=\u22128/7(2x \u2212 3)+5/7(3x \u2212 8)  \u21d22x \u2212 725x \u2212 24 \u2212 6x2=\u221287(2x \u2212 3)+57(3x \u2212 8)  \u21d22x \u2212 725x \u2212 24 \u2212 6x2=57(3x \u2212 8)\u221287(2x \u2212 3)  \u22342x \u2212 725x \u2212 24 \u2212 6x2=17(5(3x \u2212 8)\u22128(2x \u2212 3))","marks":"6","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2025>SECTION A>5","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2025","type":"Theory","sub_label":"5","group":"","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : STATISTICS","question":"The table shows the distribution of the weights (Newtons) of 100 blood donors.    Weight (N)55 - 5960 - 6566 - 7172 - 7879 - 8687 - 90Number of donors1852022278  Draw a histogram for the distribution.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Class Interval (N)  Class Boundaries (N)  Class Width  Number of Donors55 \u2013 59                 54.5 \u2013 59.5               5.0              18                   60 \u2013 65                 59.5 \u2013 65.5               6.0              5                    66 \u2013 71                 65.5 \u2013 71.5               6.0              20                   72 \u2013 78                 71.5 \u2013 78.5               7.0              22                   79 \u2013 86                 78.5 \u2013 86.5               8.0              27                  87 \u2013 90                 86.5 \u2013 90.5               4.0              8","marks":"6","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2025>SECTION A>6","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2025","type":"Theory","sub_label":"6","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : PROBABILITY","question":"If two fair dice are thrown together twice, find the probability of obtaining a product of six in the first throw and a sum of eight in the second throw.    (Please leave your answer in this form: a/b)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Key:  \u2713= Product of six  \u2717= Sum of eight    12345611, 11, 21, 31, 41, 51, 6 \u271322, 12, 22, 3 \u27132, 42, 52, 6 \u271733, 13, 2 \u27133, 33, 43, 5 \u27173, 644, 14, 24, 34, 4 \u27174, 54, 655, 15, 25, 3 \u27175, 45, 55, 66, 1 \u27136, 2 \u27176, 36, 46, 56, 6  P(Product\u00a0=6)=436=19  P(Sum\u00a0=8)=536  \u2234P(Product\u00a0=\u00a06\u00a0AND\u00a0Sum\u00a0=\u00a08)=19\u00d7536=5324","marks":"6","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2025>SECTION A>7>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2025","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : EQUATION OF MOTION","question":"A light inextensible string passes over a smooth pulley and carries masses 4 kg and 3 kg at its ends. If the masses are released from rest, calculate:    their acceleration;    [Take g = 10 ms-2]    (Please leave your answer without the unit and to 2 d.p)","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"For the 4 kg mass (moving down):    T1 = Tension in the string (upward)    m1g \u2212 T1 \u200b= m1\u200ba     4(10) \u2212 T1 = 4a    40 \u2212 T1 = 4a ----- (i)    For the 3 kg mass (moving up):    T2 \u200b= Tension in the string (upward)    T2\u200b \u2212 m2\u200bg = m2\u200ba (eq. 2)     T2 \u2212 3(10) = 3a    T2 \u2212 30 = 3a ----- (ii)    Since it's one string over a pulley:    T1 = T2 = T     40 \u2212 T = 4a ----- (iii)    T \u2212 30 = 3a ----- (iv)    Adding equations (iii) and (iv):    \u21d2 10 = 7a    \u2234a=107=1.43ms-2","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2025>SECTION A>7>b","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2025","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : EQUATION OF MOTION","question":"A light inextensible string passes over a smooth pulley and carries masses 4 kg and 3 kg at its ends. If the masses are released from rest, calculate:  their speed after 3 seconds.    [Take g = 10 ms-2]    (Please leave your answer without the unit and to 2 d.p)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"We already found the acceleration of the system:    a = 1.43\u2009ms-2     Now, we are to find the speed after 3 seconds, given:    The system starts from rest u = 0    Time t = 3\u2009s    Using the equation of motion:    v = u + at    v = 0 + 1.43(3)    v = 0 + 4.29    \u2234 v = 4.29 ms-1","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2025>SECTION A>8>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2025","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : EQUATION OF MOTION","question":"A force of F  N  acts on a body of mass 50 kg and changes its velocity from 30 ms-1 to 40 ms-1 in 6 seconds. Find the:    magnitude of the force;    [Take g = 10 ms-2]    (Please leave your answer with the unit and to 2 d.p)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Force,F=m(v - u)t  F=50(40 - 30)6  F=50(10)6  F=5006  \u2234 F = 83.33 N","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2025>SECTION A>8>b","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2025","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : EQUATION OF MOTION","question":"A force of F  N  acts on a body of mass 50 kg and changes its velocity from 30 ms-1 to 40 ms-1 in 6 seconds. Find the:  acceleration of the body;    [Take g = 10 ms-2]    (Please leave your answer without the unit and in this form: a/b)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"a=v - ut  a=40 - 306  a=106  \u2234 a=53ms-2","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2025>SECTION A>8>c","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2025","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"FINAL","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : EQUATION OF MOTION","question":"A force of F  N  acts on a body of mass 50 kg and changes its velocity from 30 ms-1 to 40 ms-1 in 6 seconds. Find the:  distance covered in 9 seconds when the initial velocity is 30 ms-1.    [Take g = 10 ms-2]    (Please leave your answer with the unit and to 1 d.p)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Using the equation of motion:    s=ut+12at2  s=30(9)+12\u00d753\u00d792  s=270+56\u00d781  s = 270 + 67.5    \u2234 s = 337.5 m","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2025>SECTION B>9>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2025","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : INTEGRATION","question":"Given that \u222bm-1 (2x2 - x - 3)  dx  = -9/2 , where m is an integer, find the value of m.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"\u222bm-1(2x2-x-3)dx=-92  On integrating:    \u21d2(2x33-x22-3x)m-1=-92  \u21d2(2(m)33-(m)22-3(m))-(2(-1)33-(-1)22-3(-1))=-92  \u21d2(2m33-m22-3m)-(2(-1)3-12-3(-1))=-92  \u21d2(2m33-m22-3m)-(-23-12+3)=-92  \u21d22m33-m22-3m-116=-92  \u21d22m33-m22-3m=-92+116  \u21d22m33-m22-3m=-83  Multiply by 6:    \u21d2 4m3 - 3m2 - 18m = -16    \u21d2 4m3 - 3m2 - 18m + 16 = 0    Trying m = 2:    4(2)3 \u2212 3(2)2 \u2212 18(2) +16 = 32 \u2212 12 \u2212 36 + 16 = 0 \u21d2 m = 2\u00a0is\u00a0a\u00a0root.    Only m = 2 is a rational root; the other two are irrational.    \u2234 m = 2","marks":"6","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2025>SECTION B>9>b","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2025","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : INTEGRATION","question":"Solve 2(log3x - 1) = log3x and y = &radic;x&nbsp; + 1 simultaneously.    (Please leave your answer in this form: x = a, y = b)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"2(log3x - 1) = log3x ----- (i)     y = &radic;x&nbsp; + 1 ----- (ii)    Solving the logarithmic equation:    2log3x - 2 = log3x    2log3x - log3x = 2    log3x = 2    x = 32    x = 9    Substituting x = 9 into the second equation:    y = &radic;9&nbsp; + 1    y = 3 + 1    y = 4    \u2234 x = 9, y = 4","marks":"7","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2025>SECTION B>10>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2025","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : PERMUTATION AND COMBINATIONS.~~PURE MATHEMATICS : SEQUENCES AND SERIES","question":"Given that 8Cx , 7Cx and 7/6(6Cx) form the first three consecutive terms of an exponential sequence (G.P.), find the:    value of x;","images":[],"marking_scheme":"T1=8Cx=8!(8 - x)!x!  T2=7Cx=7!(7 - x)!x!  T3=76(6Cx)=76\u00d76!(6 - x)!x!  commonratio,r=T3T2=T2T1  \u21d276\u00d76!(6 - x)!x!\u00f77!(7 - x)!x!=7!(7 - x)!x!\u00f78!(8 - x)!x!  \u21d276\u00d76!(6 - x)!x!\u00d7(7 - x)!x!7!=7!(7 - x)!x!\u00d7(8 - x)!x!8!  \u21d276\u00d76!(6 - x)!\u00d7(7 - x)!7!=7!(7 - x)!\u00d7(8 - x)!8!  \u21d276\u00d76!(6 - x)!\u00d7(7 - x)!7 \u00d7 6!=7!(7 - x)!\u00d7(8 - x)!8 \u00d7 7!  \u21d276\u00d71(6 - x)!\u00d7(7 - x)!7=1(7 - x)!\u00d7(8 - x)!8  \u21d276\u00d71(6 - x)!\u00d7(7 - x)(7 - x - 1)!7=1(7 - x)!\u00d7(8 - x)(8 - x - 1)!8  \u21d276\u00d71(6 - x)!\u00d7(7 - x)(6 - x)!7=1(7 - x)!\u00d7(8 - x)(7 - x)!8  \u21d276\u00d711\u00d7(7 - x)7=11\u00d7(8 - x)8  \u21d276\u00d7(7 - x)7=(8 - x)8  \u21d216\u00d7(7 - x)=(8 - x)8  \u21d2(7 - x)6=(8 - x)8  \u21d26(8-x)=8(7-x)  \u21d248-6x=56-8x  \u21d248-56=-8x+6x  \u21d2-8=-2x  \u21d2x=-8-2  \u2234x=4","marks":"6","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2025>SECTION B>10>b","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2025","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : PERMUTATION AND COMBINATIONS.~~PURE MATHEMATICS : SEQUENCES AND SERIES","question":"Given that 8Cx , 7Cx and 7/6(6Cx) form the first three consecutive terms of an exponential sequence (G.P.), find the:  common ratio of the sequence;    (Please leave your answer in this form: a/b)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"x = 4 [from 10(a)]    T1=8Cx=8!(8 - x)!x!=8!(8 - 4)!4!=8!4!4!=70  T2=7Cx=7!(7 - x)!x!=7!(7 - 4)!4!=7!3!4!=35  T3=76(6Cx)=76\u00d76!(6 - x)!x!=76\u00d76!(6 - 4)!4!=76\u00d76!2!4!=76\u00d715=17.5  commonratio,r=T3T2orT2T1  \u2234r=T2T1=3570=12","marks":"4","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2025>SECTION B>10>c","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2025","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : PERMUTATION AND COMBINATIONS.~~PURE MATHEMATICS : SEQUENCES AND SERIES","question":"Given that 8Cx , 7Cx and 7/6(6Cx) form the first three consecutive terms of an exponential sequence (G.P.), find the:  sum of the first ten terms of the sequence.    (Please leave your answer to 2 d.p)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Sn=a(1 - rn)1 - r  a=T1=70  r=12  S10=70(1 - (1/2)10)1 - 1/2  S10=70(1 - 1/1024)1/2  S10=70(1023/1024)1/2  S10=35805/5121/2  S10=35805512\u00d72  \u2234S10=35805256=139.86","marks":"3","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2025>SECTION B>11>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2025","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : SURDS","question":"Express(4 + &radic;7&nbsp;4 - &radic;7&nbsp;)2-(4 - &radic;7&nbsp;4 + &radic;7&nbsp;)2  in the form p + q &radic;7&nbsp;, where p and q are real numbers.    (Please leave your answer in this form: p = a, q = b/c)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"(4 + &radic;7&nbsp;4 - &radic;7&nbsp;)2-(4 - &radic;7&nbsp;4 + &radic;7&nbsp;)2  From a2 - b2 = (a + b)(a - b):    =((4 + &radic;7&nbsp;4 - &radic;7&nbsp;)+(4 - &radic;7&nbsp;4 + &radic;7&nbsp;))((4 + &radic;7&nbsp;4 - &radic;7&nbsp;)-(4 - &radic;7&nbsp;4 + &radic;7&nbsp;))  =((4 + &radic;7&nbsp;)2 + (4 - &radic;7&nbsp;)2(4 - &radic;7&nbsp;)(4 + &radic;7&nbsp;))((4 + &radic;7&nbsp;)2 - (4 - &radic;7&nbsp;)2(4 - &radic;7&nbsp;)(4 + &radic;7&nbsp;))  =(16 + 8&radic;7&nbsp; + 7 + 16 - 8&radic;7&nbsp; + 742 - (&radic;7&nbsp;)2)(16 + 8&radic;7&nbsp; + 7 - (16 - 8&radic;7&nbsp; + 7)42 - (&radic;7&nbsp;)2  =(469)(16&radic;7&nbsp;9)  =736&radic;7&nbsp;81  \u2234(4 + &radic;7&nbsp;4 - &radic;7&nbsp;)2-(4 - &radic;7&nbsp;4 + &radic;7&nbsp;)2=0+73681&radic;7&nbsp;  \u2234p=0andq=73681","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2025>SECTION B>11>b>i","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2025","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : FUNCTIONS","question":"Two functions  f  and  g  are defined on the set of real numbers by      f :x\u2192\u221a(16 - x2x2 + 4)and g :x\u2192x2 - 48 - x2,x\u2260\u00b12&radic;2&nbsp;.   Find:    the domain of  f ;    (Please leave your answer in this form: [a, b] instead of a \u2264 x \u2264 b)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"We are given the function:    f(x)=\u221a(16 - x2x2 + 4)  We are to find the domain of f - that is, all real values of x for which f(x) is defined.  Since f(x) involves a square root, the expression inside the square root must be non-negative:    16 - x2x2 + 4\u22650  Also, the denominator x2 + 4 \u2260 0 must hold.    But:    X2 + 4 > 0 for all real x    So we never divide by zero - great.    Solving the inequality:    16 - x2x2 + 4\u22650  Since x2 + 4 > 0 always, the sign of the entire expression is determined by the numerator only:    So we need:    16 - x2 \u2265 0     \u21d2 x2 \u2264 16     \u21d2 x = &radic;16&nbsp;    \u21d2 x = \u00b14    \u21d2 \u22124 \u2264 x \u2264 4","marks":"4","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2025>SECTION B>11>b>ii","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2025","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : FUNCTIONS","question":"Two functions  f  and  g  are defined on the set of real numbers by      f :x\u2192\u221a(16 - x2x2 + 4)and g :x\u2192x2 - 48 - x2,x\u2260\u00b12&radic;2&nbsp;.   Find:   g  o  f (x).","images":[],"marking_scheme":"We are given two functions:     f :x\u2192\u221a(16 - x2x2 + 4)   g :x\u2192x2 - 48 - x2,x\u2260\u00b12&radic;2&nbsp;    g  o  f (x) =  g ( f (x))    g(f(x))=(f(x))2 - 48 - (f(x))2   f :x\u2192\u221a(16 - x2x2 + 4)\u21d216 - x2x2 + 4  g(f(x))=(16 - x2/x2 + 4)2 - 48 - (16-x2/x2 + 4)2  Simplifying numerator and denominator:    Numerator:    16 - x2x2 + 4-4=16 - x2 - 4(x2 + 4)  =16 - x2 - 4x2 - 16x2 + 4=-5x2x2 + 4  Denominator:    8-16 - x2x2 + 4=8(x2 + 4) - (16 - x2)\u200bx2 + 4   =8x2 + 32 - 16 + x2x2 + 4=9x2 + 16x2 + 4  Combine:    g(f(x))=-5x2x2 + 4\u00f79x2 + 16x2 + 4  g(f(x))=-5x2x2 + 4\u00d7x2 + 49x2 + 16  \u2234g(f(x))=-5x29x2 + 16","marks":"6","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2025>SECTION B>12","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2025","type":"Theory","sub_label":"12","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : STATISTICS","question":"If the mean and standard deviation of the numbers x, 2.5, 4, y and 7 are 4 and &radic;31/10&nbsp; respectively. Find the values of x and y where x    (Please leave your answer in this form: x = a, y = b)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Given:  x  = 4, S.D = &radic;31/10&nbsp;     x =x + 2.5 + y + 4 + 75  \u21d2x + 2.5 + y + 4 + 75=4  \u21d2 13.5 + x + y = 20    \u21d2 x + y = 6.5 ----- (i)    S.D=&radic;3110&nbsp;  Variance=S.D2=3110  Variance=(x - 4)2 + (2.5 - 4)2 + (4 - 4)2 + (y - 4)2 + (7 - 4)25  \u21d2(x - 4)2 + (2.5 - 4)2 + (4 - 4)2 + (y - 4)2 + (7 - 4)25=3110  \u21d2(x - 4)2 + 2.25 + 0 + (y - 4)2 + 95=3110  \u21d2(x-4)2+2.25+0+(y-4)2+9=3110\u00d75  \u21d2 (x - 4)2 + (y - 4)2 + 11.25 = 15.5    \u21d2 (x - 4)2 + (y - 4)2 = 4.25 ----- (ii)    From equation (i):    \u21d2 y = 6.5 - x ----- (iii)    Substitute (6.5 - x) for y in equation (ii)    \u21d2 (x - 4)2 + ((6.5 - x) - 4)2 = 4.25    \u21d2 (x - 4)2 + (2.5 - x)2 = 4.25    \u21d2 (x2 - 8x + 16) + (6.25 - 5x + x2) = 4.25    \u21d2 x2 - 8x + 16 + x2 - 5x + 6.25 = 4.25    \u21d2 2x2 - 13x + 22.25 = 4.25    \u21d2 2x2 - 13x + 18 = 0    Let's solve for using the quadratic formula:    x=-b \u00b1 &radic;b2 - 4ac&nbsp;2a  a = 2, b = -13 and c = 18    \u21d2x=-(-13) \u00b1 &radic;(-13)2 - 4(2)(18)&nbsp;2(2)  \u21d2x=13 \u00b1 &radic;169 - 144&nbsp;4  \u21d2x=13 \u00b1 &radic;25&nbsp;4  \u21d2x=13 \u00b1 54  \u21d2x=13 + 54orx=13 - 54  \u21d2x=184orx=84  \u21d2 x = 4.5 or x = 2    From equation (iii):    If x = 4.5    \u21d2 y = 6.5 - 4.5    \u21d2 y = 2    But x    If x = 2    \u21d2 y = 6.5 - 2    \u21d2 y = 4.5    Here, 2    \u2234 x = 2, y = 4.5","marks":"13","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2025>SECTION B>13>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2025","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : PERMUTATION AND COMBINATIONS.","question":"An association is made up of 10 journalists and 9 engineers. If a committee of 4 members is to be formed from the association, find the probability that it will consist of;    at least two engineers;    (Please leave your answer in this form: a/b)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The total number of ways to choose 4 members out of 19 (10 journalists + 9 engineers) is given by the combination formula:    Totalcommittees=19C4=19!(19 - 4)!4!=19!15!4!=3876  Favorable Committees with \"At Least Two Engineers\"    This includes committees with:    Exactly 2 engineers and 2 journalists: 9C2 \u00d7 10C2 = 36 \u00d7 45 = 1620     Exactly 3 engineers and 1 journalist: 9C3 \u00d7 10C1 = 84 \u00d7 10 = 840    Exactly 4 engineers and 0 journalists: 9C4 \u00d7 10C0 = 126 \u00d7 1 = 126    Total Favorable Committees:    1620 + 840 + 126 = 2586    Probability=Favorable committeesTotal committees  \u2234P(atleasttwoengineers)=25863876=431646","marks":"4","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2025>SECTION B>13>b","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2025","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : PERMUTATION AND COMBINATIONS.","question":"An association is made up of 10 journalists and 9 engineers. If a committee of 4 members is to be formed from the association, find the probability that it will consist of;  75% journalists;    (Please leave your answer in this form: a/b)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Total Number of Possible Committees    The total number of ways to choose 4 members out of 19 (10 journalists + 9 engineers) is:    Totalcommittees=19C4=19!(19 - 4)!4!=19!15!4!=3876  A 4-member committee with 75% journalists means:    75% of 4 = 3 journalists    So, the committee must consist of exactly 3 journalists.    Since the committee has 4 members in total, the remaining 4 \u2212 3 = 1 member must be an engineer.    Therefore, we need to find the number of ways to form a committee with exactly 3 journalists and 1 engineer.    Favorable Committees with \"75% journalists\":    Exactly 3 journalists and 1 engineer: 10C3 \u00d7 9C1 = 120 \u00d7 9 = 1080  Probability=Favorable committeesTotal committees  \u2234P(75%journalists)=10803876=90323","marks":"4","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2025>SECTION B>13>c","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2025","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : PERMUTATION AND COMBINATIONS.","question":"An association is made up of 10 journalists and 9 engineers. If a committee of 4 members is to be formed from the association, find the probability that it will consist of;  odd number of engineers.    (Please leave your answer in this form: a/b)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Total Number of Possible Committees    The total number of ways to choose 4 members out of 19 (10 journalists + 9 engineers) is:    Totalcommittees=19C4=19!(19 - 4)!4!=19!15!4!=3876  Favorable Committees with Odd Numbers of Engineers    An odd number of engineers in a 4-member committee can be:    1 engineer and 3 journalists: 9C1 \u00d7 10C3 = 9 \u00d7 120 = 1080    3 engineers and 1 journalist: 9C3 \u00d7 10C1 = 84 \u00d7 10 = 840    Total Favorable Committees:    1080 + 840 = 1920    Probability=Favorable committeesTotal committees  \u2234P(oddnumberofengineers)=19203876=160323","marks":"5","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2025>SECTION B>14>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2025","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : STATICS","question":"Five forces acting on a particle are represented by (2i + 3j), (4i - 7j), (-5i + 8j), (i + j) and (pi + qj), where p, q \u2208 R. If the particle is in equilibrium, find the values of p and q.    (Please leave your answer in this form: p = a, q = b)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"We are given five forces acting on a particle:    F1 = 2i + 3j; F2 = 4i - 7j; F3 = -5i + 8j; F4 = i + j; F5 = pi + qj    The condition for equilibrium is that the vector sum of all forces must be zero, i.e.:    F1 + F2 + F3 + F4 + F5 = 0    Adding the i-components:    2 + 4 + (\u22125) + 1 + p = (2 + 4 \u2212 5 + 1) + p = 2 + p    Set this equal to 0 (for equilibrium):    2 + p = 0 \u21d2 p = \u22122    Adding the j-components:    3 + (\u22127) + 8 + 1 + q = (3 \u2212 7 + 8 + 1) + q = 5 + q    Set this equal to 0 (for equilibrium):    5 + q = 0 \u21d2 q = \u22125    \u2234 p = -2, q = -5","marks":"4","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2025>SECTION B>14>b>i","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2025","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"FINAL","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : VECTORS","question":"WXYZ is a parallelogram whose vertices are W(-1, 1), X(m, n), Y(5, -7) and Z(2, 4). Find the:    values of m and n;    (Please leave your answer in this form: m = a, n = b)","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"In a parallelogram, the diagonals bisect each other. This means that the midpoint of one diagonal is the same as the midpoint of the other diagonal.    Let's find the midpoint of the diagonals WY and XZ.    1. Midpoint of WY:     The coordinates of W are (\u22121, 1) and Y are (5, \u22127).     The midpoint formula for two points (x1\u200b, y1\u200b) and (x2\u200b, y2\u200b) is     (x1\u200b + x22\u200b\u200b,y1 \u200b+ y22\u200b\u200b).  MidpointofWY=(\u22121 + 52\u200b,1 + (\u22127)2\u200b)=(42\u200b,\u22126)2\u200b)=(2,\u22123)  2. Midpoint of XZ:     The coordinates of X are (m, n) and Z are (2, 4).     MidpointofXZ=(m + 22\u200b,n + 42\u200b)  3. Equating the midpoints:     Since the diagonals bisect each other, the midpoint of WY must be equal to the midpoint of XZ.     (2,\u22123)=(m + 22\u200b,n + 42\u200b)  Equating the x-coordinates:     2=m + 22\u200b  4 = m + 2     m = 4 \u2212 2     m = 2    Equating the y-coordinates:     \u22123=n + 42\u200b  \u22126 = n + 4     n = \u22126 \u2212 4     n = \u221210    Thus, the values are m = 2 and n = \u221210.","marks":"6","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2025>SECTION B>14>b>ii","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2025","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : VECTORS","question":"WXYZ is a parallelogram whose vertices are W(-1, 1), X(m, n), Y(5, -7) and Z(2, 4). Find the:  unit vector in the direction of  XY","images":[],"marking_scheme":"To find the unit vector in the direction of XY, we first need to:    1.\tDetermine the coordinates of X. (We found these in the previous step).    2.\tFind the vector XY.    3.\tCalculate the magnitude of vector XY.    4.\tDivide the vector XY by its magnitude.    From the previous calculation, we found the values of m and n. m = 2 and n = \u221210.     So, the coordinates of X are (2, \u221210). The coordinates of Y are (5, \u22127).    1. Find the vector XY:     The vector from point A(x1\u200b, y1\u200b) to point B(x2\u200b, y2\u200b) is given by AB = (x2 \u200b\u2212 x1\u200b)I + (y2\u200b \u2212 y1\u200b)j.     Vector XY = (5 \u2212 2)i + (\u22127 \u2212 (\u221210))j     Vector XY = (3)i + (\u22127 + 10)j     Vector XY = 3i + 3j    2. Calculate the magnitude of vector XY:     The magnitude of a vector ai + bj is &radic;a2 + b2&nbsp;\u200b.     \u2223XY\u2223 = 32 + 32\u200b     \u2223XY\u2223 = 9 + 9\u200b     \u2223XY\u2223 = 18\u200b     \u2223XY\u2223 = &radic;9 \u00d7 2&nbsp;\u200b     \u2223XY\u2223 = 3&radic;2&nbsp;\u200b    3. Find the unit vector in the direction of XY:     AunitvectorinthedirectionofavectorVisgivenbyV^=V/(V)/\u200b.  UnitvectorindirectionofXY=\u200b3i + 3j3&radic;2&nbsp;\u200b  We can simplify this by dividing both terms in the numerator by 3:     Unitvector=\u200b3(i + j)3&radic;2&nbsp;\u200b  Unitvector=\u200bi + j&radic;2&nbsp;\u200b  This can also be written as:     Unitvector=1&radic;2&nbsp;\u200bi+1&radic;2&nbsp;\u200bj  Or, by rationalizing the denominator:   Unitvector=&radic;2&nbsp;2\u200b\u200bi+&radic;2&nbsp;2\u200b\u200bj  The unit vector in the direction of XY is     1&radic;2&nbsp;\u200bi+1&radic;2&nbsp;\u200bjor&radic;2&nbsp;2\u200b\u200bi+&radic;2&nbsp;2\u200b.","marks":"3","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2025>SECTION B>15>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2025","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : EQUATION OF MOTION","question":"An object is thrown vertically upwards from the top of a building 20 m high. If the object passes the point it was thrown after 4 seconds on its way down, find the:    velocity at which the object was thrown;    [Take g = 10 ms-2]    (Please leave your answer with the unit e.g. 123.123 J/K)","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Time, t, from the top of the building to the maximum throw point = 4/2 = 2 sec    Final velocity, v, at the maximum throw point = 0 ms-1    g = -10 ms-2 (downward)    u = ?    v = u + gt    \u21d2 0 = u + (-10)(2)    \u21d2 0 = u - 10(2)    \u21d2 0 = u - 20    \u2234 u = 20 ms-1","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2025>SECTION B>15>b","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2025","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : EQUATION OF MOTION","question":"An object is thrown vertically upwards from the top of a building 20 m high. If the object passes the point it was thrown after 4 seconds on its way down, find the:  time taken when the object is 10 m above the level it was thrown;    [Take g = 10 ms-2]    (Please leave your answers with the unit, to 2 d.p and in this form: (a N, b N). Where a )","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Initial velocity, u = 20 ms-1    Height above throw point, s = 10 m    Acceleration due to gravity, g = -10 ms-2 (downward)    t = ?    s=ut+12gt2  \u21d2-10=20t+12\u00d7-10\u00d7t2  \u21d210=20t-12\u00d710\u00d7t2  \u21d2 10 = 20t - 5t2    \u21d2 5t2 - 20t + 10 = 0    Divide by 5:    \u21d2 t2 - 4t + 2 = 0    Using the quadratic formula:    t=-b \u00b1 &radic;b2 - 4ac&nbsp;2a  Here, a = 1, b = \u22124, and c = 2:    \u21d2t=-(-4) \u00b1 &radic;(-4)2 - 4(1)(2)&nbsp;2(1)  \u21d2t=4 \u00b1 &radic;16 - 8&nbsp;2  \u21d2t=4 \u00b1 &radic;8&nbsp;2  \u21d2t=4 \u00b1 2&radic;2&nbsp;2  \u21d2 t = 2 \u00b1 &radic;2&nbsp;    The object reaches 10 m above the throw point at two times:    On its way up:     t = 2 - &radic;2&nbsp; \u2248 0.59 s    On its way down:     t = 2 + &radic;2&nbsp; \u2248 3.41 s","marks":"3","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2025>SECTION B>15>c","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2025","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"FINAL","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : EQUATION OF MOTION","question":"An object is thrown vertically upwards from the top of a building 20 m high. If the object passes the point it was thrown after 4 seconds on its way down, find the:  time taken when the object is 10 m below the level it was thrown;    [Take g = 10 ms-2]    (Please leave your answer with the unit and to 2 d.p)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"\"Because displacement, velocity, and acceleration are vectors, we treat upward directions as positive and downward directions as negative.\"    u = +20 ms-1 (upward), s = -10 m (since it's below); g = -10 ms-1 (downward)    s=ut+12gt2  \u21d2-10=20t+12\u00d7-10\u00d7t2  \u21d2-10=20t-12\u00d710\u00d7t2  \u21d2 -10 = 20t - 5t2    \u21d2 5t2 - 20t - 10 = 0    Divide by 5:    \u21d2 t2 - 4t - 2 = 0    Using the quadratic formula:    t=-b \u00b1 &radic;b2 - 4ac&nbsp;2a  Here, a = 1, b = \u22124, and c = -2:    \u21d2t=-(-4) \u00b1 &radic;(-4)2 - 4(1)(-2)&nbsp;2(1)  \u21d2t=4 \u00b1 &radic;16 + 8&nbsp;2  \u21d2t=4 \u00b1 &radic;24&nbsp;2  \u21d2t=4 \u00b1 2&radic;6&nbsp;2  \u21d2 t = 2 \u00b1 &radic;6&nbsp;    The object reaches 10 m below the throw point at:    t = 2 + &radic;6&nbsp; \u2248 2 + 2.45 = 4.45\u2009s    (Discard t = 2 - &radic;6&nbsp; \u200b since it's negative and not physically meaningful.)","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2025>SECTION B>15>d","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2025","type":"Theory","sub_label":"d","group":"FINAL","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : EQUATION OF MOTION","question":"An object is thrown vertically upwards from the top of a building 20 m high. If the object passes the point it was thrown after 4 seconds on its way down, find the:  velocity with which the object hits the ground.    [Take g = 10 ms-2]    (Please leave your answer with the unit and to 2 d.p e.g. 123.123 J/K)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"u = 20 ms-1 (upward); g = 10 ms-2 (downward); s = 20 m (downward)    v2 = u2 + 2gs    Taking upward as positive and downward as negative    \u21d2 v2 = 202 + 2(-10)(-20)    \u21d2 v2 = 400 + 400    \u21d2 v2 = 800    \u21d2 v = &radic;800&nbsp;    \u21d2 v = 4&radic;50&nbsp;    \u2234 v \u2248 \u00b128.28 ms-1    Since the object is moving downward when it hits the ground, its velocity is:    \u221228.28\u2009ms-1 (taking upward as positive)","marks":"4","difficulty":"1"}];